    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-22T09:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-22T09:44:00-05:00" n="542"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d542">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/2760: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Walton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-22T14:00:00-00:44"
                            >May 22, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 23—12:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>47. Bank of Monrovia’s application for navicert to ship 419 ounces of gold
                    refused on the ground that bank has not agreed not to transfer funds for
                    Germans. British Chargé d’Affaires has instructed traders not to ship gold
                    through Bank of Monrovia but through two British firms.</p>
                <p>British Chargé d’Affaires in the presence of prominent Liberian and two Europeans
                    today avowed he was out to get Harvey Firestone and that he paid no attention to
                    Liberian neutrality because Liberia was not strong enough to enforce it.</p>
                <p>Please advise this Legation if the British Chargé d’Affaires is acting under
                    instructions of his Government; also should this Legation refuse British
                    applicant consular invoices for gold shipments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Walton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
